ling, weather assessment, computer skills => good reliability, technical, calm under pressure. Negatives: weak memory for numbers (could affect calculations), nasty remarks (teamwork issue). Overall good but teamwork and memory issues.\n\nCandidate C: quick correct decisions, calm in crisis, understands tech => good decision-making, calm, technical. Negatives: communication difficulty, egocentric, unwilling to further education => teamwork and development issues. Overall decent but teamwork concerns.\n\nCandidate D: responds adequately to unexpected, concentration, problem solving, responsibility => good reliability, technical problem solving, decision-making. Negatives: know-it-all (teamwork), hot temper (pressure). Could affect calmness under pressure.\n\nWe need to weigh seriousness. For long-distance flights, teamwork and calm under pressure are critical. Memory for numbers is important for navigation. Hot temper could be dangerous. Show-off maybe less critical but could affect crew. Not open to new ideas could hinder adaptation to new tech.\n\nWhich candidate best balances? Candidate B has strong stress handling, conscientious, good weather assessment, but memory weakness and nasty remarks. Memory for numbers is important; could be mitigated? But we cannot mitigate. Candidate D has hot temper, know-it-all, which could affect crew cooperation and calmness. Candidate C has communication difficulty and egocentric, also not willing to further education. Candidate A has show-off and not open to new ideas.\n\nWhich is least severe negatives? Let's compare severity: \n- Show-off vs not open to new ideas: may affect crew but perhaps less severe than hot temper or nasty remarks.\n- Nasty remarks directly harms teamwork.\n- Hot temper could affect calmness under pressure.\n- Memory for numbers could cause errors.\n\nThus candidate A may be best despite show-off and closedness. He has strong anticipation, spatial vision, leadership, complex connections. Those are valuable